cs.DS, cs.AI, cs.GT, cs.LG, cs.RO. 

The paper deals with a problem in optimization (maximizing expected reward subject to constraints) with stochastic elements (random processing times), which suggests it could belong to cs.DS (data structures and algorithms) or cs.RO (robotics and automation). The use of non-anticipatory policies and adaptivity gap also suggests a connection to cs.AI (artificial intelligence) and cs.LG (machine learning). Finally, the paper involves a theoretical analysis of the problem and its complexity, which could place it in cs.GT (computational complexity and cryptography).
